  "text": "whereũ(x) is the approximation to the exact solution u(x), and a i is a quadrature weight based on the boundary sampling. More accurate solutions require more accurate boundary quadrature, typically resulting in more function evaluations. This summation must be evaluated at every point where we wish to knowũ(x). Solving for the variables a i in Equation 4 typically requires the solution of a dense N -dimensional linear system, where N is the number of fundamental solution sources. Techniques like the fast multipole method [CITATION_1] and adaptive cross approximation [CITATION_2] can significantly reduce the computational complexity by speeding up matrix multiplication and removing the need to store the matrix explicitly.",
